<dl id="n05039f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05039f">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05039f"> 39(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> angel of death kicked / aside the bucket <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n05039f"><li>FW 170.12 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n05039f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n05039f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n05039f">MS BL 47474-3</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:362 <a name="gd2" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#gd2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd2.htm#n05039f">Draft: I.7&sect;1.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"> Disease, with its gnawing pain, continued to burrow his frame. &ldquo;I was in such agony the whole time that I could have thrown myself from the pulpit,&rsquo; he said to a lady. &lsquo;<mark>I felt as though I stood upon a bucket, and that the Angel of Death was about to kick it aside</mark>,&rsquo; he said to another; and then, with an effort to be pleasant, he added: &lsquo;This reminds me of a tiny preacher who always stood upon something of that sort to enable his flock to see him.&rsquo; <small> William J. Fitz-Patrick, <a name="BURKE" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BURKE"><cite title="source">The Life of the Very Rev. Thomas N. Burke</cite></a>, (1885) II, 246</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
